               <occupation type="academic">scholar</occupation>
               <nationality type="Russia/USSR"/>
               <faith type="Orthodox"/>
               <birth when="1868"/>

               <floruit notBefore="1891" notAfter="1920">He was a renowned Russian Orientalist born
                  to provincial gentry. He studied Egyptology in the historico-philological faculty
                  of St <placeName ref="wd:Q656"/> University and completed the course in
                     <date>1891</date>. Then, he was retained as a post-graduate student, was sent
                  for studies abroad for one year. He worked in the museums of <placeName ref="wd:Q64"
                  />, <placeName ref="wd:Q90"/>, <placeName ref="wd:Q84"/>, and also <placeName ref="wd:Q38"
                  /> collecting the material for his Magister Thesis. After his return in
                     <date>1896</date>, he lectured on the history of the Ancient Orient and
                  Egyptology at St <placeName ref="wd:Q656"/> University as assistant Professor. In
                     <date>1898</date>, he obtained his Magister of General History. Turaev
                  published his first work in the field of Ethiopian Studies in <date>1897</date>
                  and since then he produced writings devoted to Ethiopian topics every year. He
                  edited and translated several Gǝʿǝz texts. </floruit>
               <death when="1920">He died at <placeName ref="wd:Q656"/> in <date>1920</date>
               </death>
            </person>
